content: Given the following mathematical function expressions, you need to calculate the indefinite integral of the function (excluding the constant C), then substitute 'x=4' into the result of the indefinite integral, and finally provide me with the integer result of the expression by rounding down. The indefinite integral of the function sin(x)/cos(sin(x)) is equal to (sin(x)/cos(x)) - ln|cos(x)| + C, where C is an arbitrary constant. To substitute 'x=4' into this result, you need to add ln(cos(4)) to the value. In general, ln(cos(x)) is equal to -ln(sin(x)) for any real number x, so the final expression is:

(-ln(sin(4)) + C) - (ln(cos(4)))

This expression will give you an integer result, which you can round down to the nearest integer. Therefore, the final result will be 13.
